Advanced Machine Learning - Easy Visa Problem Statement¶¶

Problem Statement¶

With the help of classification model:

  1. Facilitate the process of visa approvals
  2. Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  1. case_id: ID of each visa application
  2. continent: Information of continent the employee
  3. education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  4. has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  5. requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  6. no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  7. yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  8. region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  9. prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  10. unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  11. full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  12. case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

The objective of this analysis is to find patterns within the dataset to gain further understanding of the data and leverage it to choose a machine learning algorithm that can recommend a suitable profile for the applicants whose visa should be certified or denied.

#define a function to plot the boxplot and histogram for all numerical variables

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=True):
    fig, (axis_box, axis_hist) = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw ={"height_ratios":(0.25, 0.75)},figsize=figsize)
    sns.set_palette("pastel")
    #Creating 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(data=data,x=feature, ax=axis_box, showmeans=True)
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=axis_hist, kde=kde)
    axis_hist.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color='red', linestyle="dotted")
    axis_hist.axvline(data[feature].median(), color='yellow', linestyle="dashed")

#Labelled bar plots for categorical columns

def labelled_barplot(data, feature):

    #count of occurences of each unique value in the feature
    count_data = data[feature].value_counts().reset_index()
    count_data.columns = ['Feature', 'Count']

    #Calculate the % of each count
    total_count = count_data['Count'].sum()
    count_data['Percentage'] = (count_data['Count'] / total_count) * 100

    #Create the bar plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='Feature', y='Count', data=count_data)

    #adding % on the bars
    for index, row in count_data.iterrows():
        plt.text(row.name, row.Count, f"{row.Percentage:.1f}%", color ='black', ha="center")


    plt.title(f"Distribution of {feature}")
    plt.xlabel(f"{feature}")
    plt.ylabel("count")
    plt.show()

#distribution for comparing Numerical variables with target variable

def distribution_plot(data,x_var,target):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(12,10))
    target_var = data[target].unique()

    #Histogram with unique values of the target variable
    axes[0,0].set_title("distribution of target = "+ str(target_var[0]))
    sns.histplot(data=data[data[target] == target_var[0]],x = x_var,kde=True,ax=axes[0,0],stat='density')
    axes[0,1].set_title("distribution of target = "+ str(target_var[1]))
    sns.histplot(data=data[data[target] == target_var[1]],x = x_var,kde=True,ax=axes[0,1],stat='density')

    #Box plot with and without outliers
    axes[1,0].set_title("Box Plot with outliers")
    sns.boxplot(x=target, y=x_var, data=data, ax=axes[1,0])
    axes[1,1].set_title("Box Plot without outliers")
    sns.boxplot(x=target, y=x_var, data=data, ax=axes[1,1],showfliers=False)


    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#Stacked bar chart for comparing Categorical variables with target Variable

def stacked_bar_plot(data,x_var,target):

    count=data[x_var].nunique()
    sorter=data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    pd.crosstab(data[x_var],data[target],normalize='index').sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False).plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))

#define a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model

def model_performance(model, predictors, target):

    #predicting using the independant variables
    predictions = model.predict(predictors)

    #calculating the performance metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(target, predictions)
    recall = recall_score(target, predictions)
    precision = precision_score(target, predictions)
    f1 = f1_score(target, predictions)

    #creating a dataframe of metrics
    performance_metrics_df = pd.DataFrame({"Accuracy": accuracy, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1},index=[0])

    return performance_metrics_df
In [51]:
# Compute the confusion matrix

def confmat(model, predictors, target):

    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

# Plot the feature importances graph for each model

def feature_imp_plot(model,X_train):
    feature_names = list(X_train.columns)
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    plt.title('Feature Importances')
    plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color ="red", align="center")
    plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
    plt.xlabel("Relative importance")
    plt.show()

After US, shape of dataset : (11846, 21)

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. Model predicts that the visa application will get certified but in reality, the visa application should get denied. (FP - Precision)
  2. Model predicts that the visa application will not get certified but in reality, the visa application should get certified. (FN - Recall)

Which case is more important?

Both the cases are important as:

  1. If a visa is certified when it had to be denied a wrong employee will get the job position while US citizens will miss the opportunity to work on that position.

  2. If a visa is denied when it had to be certified the U.S. will lose a suitable human resource that can contribute to the economy.

How to reduce the losses?

F1 Score can be used a the metric for evaluation of the model, greater the F1 score higher are the chances of minimizing False Negatives and False Positives.

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
model10 = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=model1, param_distributions=parameters, n_iter=10, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, random_state=1)

# Fit RandomizedSearchCV
model10.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Print the best parameters
print(f'Best Parameters: {model10.best_params_}')

# Evaluate the tuned model
tuned_model10 = model10.best_estimator_
tuned_model10.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = tuned_model10.predict(X_test)

#Tuning - Adaboost Classifier with original dataset - model 19

# Initialize the base model (DecisionTreeClassifier)
base_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=1, random_state=42)  # Weak learner

# Initialize AdaBoostClassifier with base model
ada_boost_clf = AdaBoostClassifier(base_model, random_state=42)

# Define the parameter grid for RandomizedSearchCV
param_dist = {'n_estimators': [50, 150, 300], 'learning_rate': [1, 0.1, 0.5, 0.01]}

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV with F1 score as the scoring metric
model19 = RandomizedSearchCV(ada_boost_clf, param_distributions=param_dist, n_iter=10, scoring='f1',cv=5, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the model with RandomizedSearchCV
model19.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the best model found by the random search
tuned_model19 = model19.best_estimator_
tuned_model19.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = tuned_model19.predict(X_test)

Observations and Buisiness Recommendations:

  1. Overall we can see that considering F1 score of test data the models are in the order of performance using Original Dataset:
  • Gradient Boost
  • Random Forest
  • Bagging
  • Adaboost
  • Decision tree

  1. In the tuned models the top three important features to look for while certifying a visa are - Education of the employee, Job experience, and Prevailing Wage. Hence using these we can easliy shortlist the candidates in first level.

  2. Sythetic dataset proved to improve the model performance but not upto the original dataset's value.

  3. Visa Certifications can be Accepted based on:

  • Education - Atleast a Bachelor's degree or Master's are preferred.
  • Job Experience - Having a prior job experience plays a major role.
  • Prevailing wage - For employees whose visa got certified the median prevailing wage was of around ~72k.

Other Features to look at are as follows:

  • Employees with yearly wage are preferred.
  • Applications from Europe, Africa, and Asia have higher chances of visa certification
  • Region of employment - Applications in the Mid-West region have more chances of visa approval.
  • The requirement for the applicants who have passed high school is most in the South region, followed by Northeast region.
  • The requirement for Bachelor's is mostly in South region, followed by West region.
  • The requirement for Master's is most in Northeast region, followed by South region.
  • The requirement for Doctorate's is mostly in West region, followed by Northeast region.
  1. Visa Certifications can be Denied based on:
  • High school degree employees have a higher chance of getting their visa denied.
  • Continent - It has been observed that employees from South America and North America have higher chances of visa applications getting denied.
  • Job Experience - Employees with no job experience have a higher chance of visa rejection.
  • People with hourly wage are rarely granted visa.
  • People from Island region have more denied visas.
